                  {label}
                </a>
              </li>
            ))}
          </ol>
        </nav>

        {/* ── Context ── */}
        <section id="context" className="mb-12">
          <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">
            What The Helpful Dev actually is
          </h2>
          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            The premise is simple: ship one free, privacy-first web app per
            month throughout 2026. No ads, no login, no data collection. Just
            stuff that works in your browser. The site you&apos;re reading this
            on is the hub — a place to find the apps, follow the build-in-public
            journey, and subscribe for updates.
          </p>
          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            What it took a while to figure out was that the site itself needed
            the same care as the apps. The first version was essentially a
            glorified list of links. Getting from there to something with an
            actual identity took three full rewrites, a rebrand, an SEO sprint,
            a quality audit, and a pivot that redefined what the homepage was
            even trying to say.
          </p>
          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            Here&apos;s how each iteration happened and what I learned from it.
          </p>
        </section>

        {/* ── V1 ── */}
        <section id="v1" className="mb-12">
          <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">
            v1: The humble card grid (January 2026)
          </h2>
          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            The first commit landed on January 9th. It was honest in the best
            and worst sense — completely bare-bones, no pretense, and held
            together by a 2-column card grid and a disabled email input with a
            comment that read{" "}
            <code className="bg-slate-100 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono text-slate-800">
              Mailing list coming soon — bookmark this page!
            </code>
            .
          </p>

          <CodeBlock label="app/page.tsx — January 9, 2026">
{`<header className="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 py-20 text-center">
  <div className="mb-4 inline-block px-3 py-1 bg-blue-100
      text-blue-800 rounded-full text-sm font-semibold">
    TheHelpfulDev
  </div>
  <h1 className="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold mb-6">
    Free, privacy-focused tools for everyday problems.
  </h1>
  <p className="text-xl text-slate-600 mb-8 leading-relaxed">
    I build simple apps to help the community. No ads, no
    tracking, just useful code.
  </p>

  {/* Email Capture Placeholder - Connect to form service later */}
  <input
    type="email"
    placeholder="Enter your email for updates..."
    disabled
  />
  <p className="text-xs text-slate-400 mt-2">
    (Mailing list coming soon — bookmark this page!)
  </p>
</header>`}
          </CodeBlock>

          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            The app cards were white boxes with a coloured status badge (
            <code className="bg-slate-100 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono text-slate-800">
              LIVE
            </code>{" "}
            or{" "}
            <code className="bg-slate-100 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono text-slate-800">
              COMING SOON
            </code>
            ), a one-line description, and a blue button. Everything was
            blue — the badge, the button, the pill in the header. Not a cohesive
            design system, just the default instinct when you want something to
            feel &quot;techy.&quot;
          </p>

          <Callout variant="insight" icon="💡" label="What I noticed">
            The disabled email input was actually a great instinct — it set the
            expectation early that a newsletter was coming. But the design
            screamed &quot;side project&quot; rather than &quot;something worth
            returning to.&quot; There was no reason for a visitor to bookmark
            it beyond the reminder to.
          </Callout>

          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            Over the following weeks, apps got added as they shipped — unvAIl,
            then Timeagotchi. The email subscription went live. Icons got
            updated. The{" "}
            <code className="bg-slate-100 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono text-slate-800">
              COMING SOON
            </code>{" "}
            badge on Timeagotchi briefly became{" "}
            <code className="bg-slate-100 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono text-slate-800">
              BETA
            </code>
            , then back again. The commits from this phase are all prefixed{" "}
            <code className="bg-slate-100 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono text-slate-800">
              SOLID-111-NOTSOLIDLOL
            </code>{" "}
            — which, in hindsight, is a perfect summary of the energy.
          </p>
        </section>

        {/* ── V2 ── */}
        <section id="v2" className="mb-12">
          <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">
            v2: The commercial redesign — and the same-day color crisis
          </h2>
          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            By mid-March I knew the card grid had to go. Four apps were live or
            nearly live, and the site still looked like a first-year student
            project. I wanted something that felt closer to a real product
            company — a sticky navbar, alternating app showcase sections with
            live previews, a newsletter form that didn&apos;t apologize for
            existing.
          </p>
          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            I kicked off an agentic workflow with Claude: gave it the existing
            codebase as context, described the commercial-grade layout I wanted,
            and let it run. The result — shipped as a PR on March 14th — was a
            complete architectural overhaul.
          </p>

          <CodeBlock label="app/components/AppSpotlight.tsx — March 14, 2026">
{`interface AppSpotlightProps {
  icon: React.ReactNode;
  status: "live" | "beta" | "coming-soon";
  title: string;
  tagline: string;
  description: string;
  bullets: string[];
  href: string;
  ctaLabel: string;
  previewContent: React.ReactNode;
  reverse?: boolean;
}

export default function AppSpotlight({
  reverse = false,
  ...props
}: AppSpotlightProps) {
  return (
    <section className={clsx(
      "py-24 border-b border-slate-100",
      reverse && "bg-slate-50"
    )}>
      <div className={clsx(
        "max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 grid lg:grid-cols-2 gap-16 items-center",
        reverse && "lg:grid-flow-dense"
      )}>
        {/* copy column, preview column */}
      </div>
    </section>
  );
}`}
          </CodeBlock>

          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            The{" "}
            <code className="bg-slate-100 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono text-slate-800">
              AppSpotlight
            </code>{" "}
            component was the right abstraction — alternating left/right layout,
            live app previews in an iframe (with a timeout fallback for browsers
            that block them), status badges, bullet points. It still lives in
            the codebase today.
          </p>
          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            But there was a problem. Claude chose indigo as the brand color.
          </p>

          <Callout variant="warn" icon="⚠️" label="Watch out">
            When you let an AI coding assistant make design decisions in an
            agentic run, it will pick something reasonable but generic. Indigo
            is the &quot;safe default&quot; for developer tools in 2026 — it
            looks fine, it means nothing. I didn&apos;t catch it until the PR
            was merged.
          </Callout>

          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Thirty minutes after merging the redesign, I opened another session
            and replaced every indigo reference with cyan. Then I caught one
            more batch of indigo in a separate commit. Both happened on March
            14th, within hours of the original redesign landing. The git log
            tells the story in three lines:
          </p>

          <CodeBlock label="git log — March 14, 2026 (abridged)">
{`a937036 Merge pull request #3 — Redesign app hub UI
047b1d25 Indigo to cyan rebrand
046134f  Indigo to cyan rebrand`}
          </CodeBlock>

          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            Two commits. Same day. To fix the same thing. This is what happens
            when you&apos;re vibe coding at pace — you ship, you see the real
            result, you fix it. The lesson wasn&apos;t to slow down, it was to
            have a brand reference before starting a design session rather than
            after.
          </p>
        </section>

        {/* ── Logo ── */}
        <section id="logo" className="mb-12">
          <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">
            The logo that arrived at 7 AM
          </h2>
          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Also on March 14th — later that morning — the logo landed. A
            cyberpunk animated coffee mug, rendered as an SVG, dropped into{" "}
            <code className="bg-slate-100 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono text-slate-800">
              public/logo1.svg
            </code>
            . The commit message is just: &quot;Logo rebrand.&quot;
          </p>
          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            It replaced the plain text{" "}
            <code className="bg-slate-100 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono text-slate-800">
              TheHelpfulDev
            </code>{" "}
            pill in the navbar. And it immediately made the site feel like it
            belonged to something specific rather than something generic. A good
            logo does this — it&apos;s not about the art, it&apos;s about the
            signal that someone made a deliberate choice.
          </p>

          <Callout variant="key" icon="🔑" label="Key insight">
            The logo change had more impact per line of code than any other
            single commit. The redesign was 400+ lines of component work; the
            logo was one SVG file and a two-line navbar change. Visual identity
            is disproportionately load-bearing.
          </Callout>

          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            The same day also brought a round of &quot;page updates for
            rebrand&quot; — copy tweaks, color adjustments across the individual
            app pages to make sure the cyan gradient was consistent. By the end
            of March 14th, the site had gone from a blue card grid to something
            that had a genuine visual identity.
          </p>
        </section>

        {/* ── SEO & Audit ── */}
        <section id="seo-audit" className="mb-12">
          <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">
            The SEO and quality grind
          </h2>
          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            March 16th through 19th was heads-down infrastructure. Not glamorous, but necessary. Three separate Claude sessions covered different concerns:
          </p>
          <ul className="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-slate-700 mb-4">
            <li>
              <strong>SEO:</strong> JSON-LD structured data for every page,{" "}
              <code className="bg-slate-100 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono text-slate-800">
                metadata
              </code>{" "}
              exports, canonical URLs, sitemap generation tied to{" "}
              <code className="bg-slate-100 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono text-slate-800">
                lib/app-data.ts
              </code>
              , Open Graph images.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Security audit:</strong> The CSP nonce pattern (middleware
              generates a per-request nonce, Server Components read it via{" "}
              <code className="bg-slate-100 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono text-slate-800">
                headers().get(&apos;x-nonce&apos;)
              </code>
              ), safe JSON-LD injection, no{" "}
              <code className="bg-slate-100 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono text-slate-800">
                unsafe-inline
              </code>{" "}
              in{" "}
              <code className="bg-slate-100 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono text-slate-800">
                script-src
              </code>
              .
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Quality:</strong> Accessibility audit, skip-to-content
              link, newsletter retry logic with exponential backoff, a privacy
              page.
            </li>
          </ul>
          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            The SEO session produced a plan document first (
            <code className="bg-slate-100 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono text-slate-800">
              site_analysis.md
            </code>
            ), got reviewed and corrected, then the implementation followed in a
            separate session. This two-phase approach — plan, review, implement
            — was deliberate after I&apos;d seen agentic runs go sideways when
            given too much latitude at once.
          </p>

          <Callout variant="tip" icon="✅" label="Pro tip">
            For SEO and audit work, have the AI produce a written plan first.
            Review it yourself before letting it touch files. This catches
            direction problems before they become code problems. The extra step
            costs 10 minutes and saves hours.
          </Callout>

          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            The navbar also got restructured during this phase — individual app
            name links replaced by category links (Health & Wellness, Parenting,
            Games, Productivity). This was a small change that made the nav feel
            more purposeful and less like a link dump.
          </p>
        </section>

        {/* ── V3 ── */}
        <section id="v3" className="mb-12">
          <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">
            v3: Stop being a portfolio, start being a journey
          </h2>
          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            The v2 homepage had a problem I couldn&apos;t shake: it led with
            the apps. Four{" "}
            <code className="bg-slate-100 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono text-slate-800">
              AppSpotlight
            </code>{" "}
            sections, each with a full two-column layout, preview panel, bullet
            points. It looked polished, but it answered the wrong question. A
            new visitor would see four apps and think &quot;neat, a portfolio.&quot;
            They had no reason to come back.
          </p>
          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            The actual story was more interesting: 12 apps in 12 months, built
            in public, one per month, all privacy-first. That&apos;s a journey
            worth following. The homepage just wasn&apos;t telling it.
          </p>

          <BeforeAfter
            beforeLabel="v2 homepage — led with apps"
            afterLabel="v3 homepage — leads with the challenge"
            before={`// v2: four full AppSpotlight sections
<AppSpotlight title="Fasting Tracker" reverse={false} ... />
<AppSpotlight title="Potty Panda" reverse={true} ... />
<AppSpotlight title="unvAIl" reverse={false} ... />
<AppSpotlight title="Timeagotchi" reverse={true} ... />`}
            after={`// v3: challenge config drives the hero narrative
const CHALLENGE = {
  currentMonth: 3,
  totalMonths: 12,
  appsShipped: 4,
  year: 2026,
};

// Hero leads with the challenge progress card.
// Apps appear below as a compact 4-card grid.
// Latest blog post surfaces above the grid.`}
          />

          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            The pivot landed on March 31st. The hero now leads with the
            challenge — a progress bar, apps shipped, months remaining. The
            latest blog post surfaces above the app grid. The newsletter CTA
            copy changed from &quot;Stay in the loop&quot; to &quot;Follow the
            journey.&quot;
          </p>
          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            The{" "}
            <code className="bg-slate-100 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono text-slate-800">
              CHALLENGE
            </code>{" "}
            config object is a deliberate design choice — it makes updating the
            homepage each month a two-field change rather than a structural
            edit. Clear separation between data and layout.
          </p>

          <CodeBlock label="app/page.tsx — Challenge config">
{`// Challenge config — update these each month
const CHALLENGE = {
  currentMonth: 3,
  totalMonths: 12,
  appsShipped: 4,
  year: 2026,
};

// Used in the hero to drive: progress bar width, badge copy,
// "X apps shipped · Y months remaining" stats strip.`}
          </CodeBlock>

          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            The blog launched as part of this same push — a tab in the navbar,
            a list page, and the first post (a guide to working with Claude).
            The blog existed to document the journey, which fed back into the
            homepage narrative. Blog posts appear on the homepage. The homepage
            links to the blog. It became a loop rather than a dead end.
          </p>
        </section>

        {/* ── AI angle ── */}
        <section id="ai-angle" className="mb-12">
          <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">
            How AI-assisted development shaped every iteration
          </h2>
          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Every significant rewrite in this project used Claude as an AI
            coding assistant. Not as a search engine replacement, and not as an
            autocomplete — as a genuine engineering partner that could hold the
            full codebase context and execute multi-step changes autonomously.
          </p>
          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            The v2 redesign was the most agentic workflow. I provided a plan
            document, the existing code as context, and a clear output spec, and
            let it run. The result was a PR with 400+ lines of new component
            code — correct, consistent, and wired up properly to the rest of the
            app. What it missed was brand judgment: the indigo choice was
            technically fine and thematically wrong. That&apos;s a distinction
            that requires taste, not knowledge.
          </p>
          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            The SEO and audit work showed a different pattern. A single
            free-running session would have made too many decisions I hadn&apos;t
            validated. Instead I used a plan-then-implement split across two
            sessions. The first session produced a written audit with
            prioritized recommendations. I reviewed it, struck out two
            suggestions I disagreed with, and approved the rest. The second
            session implemented exactly what was approved. This pattern — AI
            proposes, human approves, AI executes — scaled better than
            unconstrained agentic runs for complex infrastructure work.
          </p>
          <p className="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            The v3 pivot was the closest to genuine co-authorship. The idea
            (journey-first homepage) came from me; Claude helped translate it
            into a structural change: what to remove, what to add, how to
            extract the blog data into a shared module, how to simplify the
            navbar. The context window was large enough to hold the full
            conversation and make it coherent across the session.
          </p>

          <Callout variant="insight" icon="💡" label="What I noticed">
            The moments where AI-assisted development failed were consistently
            about taste and brand identity — things that require accumulated
            context about what this site is trying to say. The moments where it
            succeeded were about execution: consistent implementation of an
            agreed pattern across many files. Know which job you&apos;re hiring
            it for.
          </Callout>
        </section>

        {/* ── Takeaways ── */}
        <section id="takeaways" className="mb-6">
          <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-6">
            Key takeaways
          </h2>

          <TakeawayCard number={1} title="Ship the card grid — then replace it">
            <p>
              The v1 card grid was the right first step even though it was the
              wrong final product. It got the apps live and visible. Trying to
              build a commercial-grade site before having apps to put in it
              would have been premature. Ship something embarrassing first,
              then earn the redesign.
            </p>
          </TakeawayCard>

          <TakeawayCard number={2} title="Define the brand before the first agentic design session">
            <p>
              The indigo-to-cyan same-day pivot was avoidable. If I&apos;d had a
              written brand reference — even a one-page doc with the color values
              and the &quot;why&quot; behind them — I could have included it in
              the context window from the start. The AI would have used cyan the
              first time. After this, I wrote{" "}
              <code className="bg-slate-100 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono text-slate-800">
                .claude/skills/brand/SKILL.md
              </code>
              .
            </p>
          </TakeawayCard>

          <TakeawayCard number={3} title="A config object beats a structural edit every time">
            <p>
              The{" "}
              <code className="bg-slate-100 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-sm font-mono text-slate-800">
                CHALLENGE
              </code>{" "}
              object on the homepage is a small thing that will save real time.
              Anything that changes on a regular cadence should be isolated into
              a config shape rather than buried in JSX. Months from now,
              updating the progress bar will be a two-second edit.
            </p>
          </TakeawayCard>

          <TakeawayCard number={4} title="Plan-then-implement beats unconstrained agentic runs for infrastructure">
            <p>
              For feature work and component builds, letting the AI run with a
              clear spec works well. For SEO, security, or anything touching
              shared infrastructure, produce a written plan first. Review it.
              Then execute. The checkpoint is cheap; fixing a bad direction
              mid-implementation is not.
            </p>
          </TakeawayCard>

          <TakeawayCard number={5} title="The homepage should answer 'why come back?' not just 'what is this?'">
            <p>
              The v2 homepage answered &quot;what is this?&quot; clearly. The
              v3 homepage answers &quot;why come back?&quot; — because more apps
              are shipping, the blog is documenting how, and you can follow
              along. A portfolio has no reason to return. A journey does. That
              distinction is the whole game for a build-in-public site.
            </p>
          </TakeawayCard>
        </section>

        {/* ── Footer nav ── */}
        <div className="border-t border-slate-100 pt-10 flex flex-col sm:flex-row items-start sm:items-center justify-between gap-4">
          <Link
            href="/blog"
            className="text-sm text-slate-500 hover:text-cyan-600 transition-colors"
          >
            &larr; Back to Blog
          </Link>
          <Link
            href="/"
            className="text-sm text-slate-500 hover:text-cyan-600 transition-colors"
          >
            See the apps &rarr;
          </Link>
        </div>
      </div>
    </main>
  );
}
